Buddhism does not teach racism or equivalent forms of discrimination. However, in the modern era, instances of racism within Buddhist movement have been observed.<ref name="Cheah2011p4">{{cite book|author=Joseph Cheah|title=Race and Religion in American Buddhism: White Supremacy and Immigrant Adaptation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m95oAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA4|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-984315-2|pages=4–6}}</ref>

==Buddhist texts on discrimination== 

In many Buddhist texts places emphasis on a person's deeds and qualities instead of status by birth. Majhima Nikaya 98:650 says:{{cn|date=December 2016}}

{{quotation|By birth a Brahmin is not born, by birth a non-Brahmin is not born,
By actions a Brahmin is born, by actions a non-Brahmin is born}}

