{{Islam by country}}
'''Islam in [[Guinea-Bissau]]''' is the predominant religion of the country, numbering an estimated 50%<ref>{{cite web|author=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees |url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/4cf2d096c.html |title=Refworld &#124; 2010 Report on International Religious Freedom - Guinea-Bissau |work=[[United States Department of State]]|publisher=UNHCR |date= |accessdate=2010-12-09}}</ref> of its roughly 1.4&nbsp;million citizens are followers. The vast majority are [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] of [[Maliki]] school of [[jurisprudence]], with [[Sufi]] influences. Approximately 6% [[Shia]] and 2% [[Ahmadiyya]] are also present.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pewforum.org/uploadedFiles/Topics/Religious_Affiliation/Muslim/the-worlds-muslims-full-report.pdf | title=The World's Muslims: Unity and Diversity | accessdate=August 14, 2012 | date=August 9, 2012 | publisher=Pew Forum on Religious & Public life}}</ref>

