{{Infobox Journal | title = Oriens Christianus | cover = | editor = Hubert Kaufhold, Manfred Kropp | discipline = [[Eastern Christianity]] | language = English, French, German | abbreviation = Oriens Christ. | publisher = [[Harrassowitz Verlag]] | country = Germany | frequency = Annually | history = 1901-present | openaccess = | impact = | impact-year = | website = http://www.oriens-christianus.de/ | link1 = http://www.oriens-christianus.de/inhalt.html | link1-name = Online table of contents | link2 = | link2-name = | JSTOR = | OCLC = 1642167 | LCCN = unk83072246 | CODEN = | ISSN = 0340-6407 | eISSN = }} {{For|the publication ''Oriens christianus in quatuor patriarchatus digestus''|Michel Le Quien}} '''''Oriens Christianus''''' is an [[academic journal]] established in 1901 by [[Otto Harrassowitz]] with [[Asian studies|Asian]] and [[oriental studies]] as the major focus.<ref>The original subtitle was "Römische Halbjahr Hefte für die Kunde of christlichen Easts ', which later became simply" Hefte für die Kunde of christlichen Easts'.</ref> <ref>It was founded January 25, 1876 to mark the hundredth anniversary of the birth of writer and Catholic historian Joseph Görres, in his hometown. There has been a Görres Institute in [[Rome]] since 1887.</ref>It was edited by [[Carl Anton Baumstark|Anton Baumstark]] (1872-1948).<ref>{{cite journal | title = Reviews | author = S. P. Brock | journal = [[The Journal of Theological Studies]] | year = 1973 | volume = XXIV | issue = 1 | pages =237–238 | doi = 10.1093/jts/XXIV.1.237 }}</ref> The current [[editors-in-chief]] are Hubert Kaufhold ([[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich]]) and Manfred Kropp ([[University of Mainz]]).
Its domain is the [[Christian East]] excluding [[Greek Orthodox|Greek]] and Slavic [[Christendom]] (covered by other reviews), that is to say the [[Middle East]] from [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and [[Armenia]] to [[Ethiopia]], Asian Christian communities and to [[India]] and [[China]]. According to the founder of the program, all elements of the spiritual and material culture of the Christian communities of the East can be addressed. The journal publishes background articles, minutes of reading, but also source-texts in the various languages of Eastern Christendom. Articles can be written in different languages.
The review was led until 1941 (with brief interruptions) by its founder Carl Anton Baumstark, who has published 140 feature articles and 145 book reviews accounts. == References == {{reflist}}
